<br>
“I have been informed, that I may have been a bit hasty in posting the writ.” Bliss explained to the guards, shuffling nervously, and using a lifetime of experience gained in bootlicking at the temple to add life to her role. “I have come to apologize to your matron.”<br>
<br>
The guards laughed cruelly. As she shuffled in one rudely slapped her bottom like a common harlot. She marked that one for a particularly painful death.<br>
<br>
Their mother was busy tying up loose ends. During the night they had accounted for nearly all members of the Vlos’Shannaal. There were only a few unaccounted for and she had a good idea where to find them. There would be no mistakes made on this night.<br>
<br>
As before, Bliss was allowed to wander freely through the house. She went directly to the matron’s quarters. She felt the presence of her brothers in the hallway though they remained invisible. She knocked softly, knowing such a timid knock was more likely to gather the ire of her target.<br>
<br>
The door jerked open abruptly. The house matron swayed in the doorway, her bloodshot eyes took in the apologetic cleric standing before her. “So you have come back to beg for forgiveness eh?” Her smile was cruel as she motioned for Bliss to follow her into the room.<br>
<br>
“I did not understand your position.” Bliss began.<br>
<br>
“Of course you didn’t, what would a church bureaucrat know about real power!” The matron slapped Bliss. “We have connections to all the families of Neriak, our position is secure, none would dare challenge us.”<br>
<br>
“You mean you can blackmail and threaten.” Bliss cringed.<br>
<br>
“Indeed, what would a houseless nothing know of influence.” The matron crowed. “To attack us it to see your own name dragged through the muck of the street.” She turned and sauntered over to the bed. “Some houses possess the power to kill others through might, we can do worse than litter the street with corpses, we can destroy the reputation of any house that dares challenge our position, and we all know that reputation is more important than life.&quot;<br>
<br>
“I just want you to know…” Bliss began but was interrupted by the ranting of the house matron.<br>
<br>
“You want me to know that you are sorry you ever bothered to come here and attempt to squeeze platinum from the Vlos’Shannaal. You want to say that your superiors have reprimanded you and that you are at my disposal for as long as I like, in atonement for your transgressions. Isn’t that right little one?”<br>
<br>
“I want you to know that house Waes’Harventar sends its warmest regards, and thanks you for the opportunity to gather the blessing of the church.”<br>
<br>
The matron could hear her heart beating so intense was the quiet. Her parents had warned her that this day could come, had urged her to stay vigilant, but there was always a party to organize, a minor noble to compromise, she had ceased to fear as her files filled with juicy bits of information coaxed out between the groans and pants of those who frequented her house. No active house would dare move against the Vlos’Shannaal, it was true, the risk was too great. But a dead house, that was something else entirely, she had no protection from the dead.<br>
<br>
“Let me…” She began, pleading desperately, only to be interrupted by a brutal slap.<br>
<br>
“You want me to listen as you beg for your life. I have no interest in the wind of a harlot. I am interested in your blood. It is time the Blood Chalice was put to its proper use.” Bliss bent down and picked up the chalice, it was warm in her hand, eager to be filled.<br>
<br>
The matron saw her opportunity, she had not risen to the top of her house on her charms alone. Her right hand crept down to the bracer on her left wrist, she kept a knife there, small and dusted with deadly poison. The blade was not there.<br>
<br>
As she drew in a breath to scream for help a solid blow to her back knocked her to her knees. Strong hands gripped her arms, pulling them behind her. A quick spell from the cleric rooted her to the spot, unable to move. <br>
<br>
“Hold the cup steady.” Came a harsh voice behind her.<br>
<br>
A young Teir’Dal strode into her field of view. All thoughts of resistance fled. Raw fear numbed her mind.<br>
<br>
“It’s a shame you won’t be able to sing for us pretty one, but I am sure we will find some in your house up to the challenge.” He said. The knife caressed her throat, blood splurted wildly, painting the walls, the floor and the chalice, which began to glow with a vibrant purple aura. The matron’s last thoughts were ‘what a pretty color.’ As her soul was claimed by the god of hate, the first in a long series of sacrifices that night.<br>
<br>
The Waes’Harventhars had planned well. Nearly all the house members were too drunk or exhausted from other activites to resist. And so it was that the Vlos’Shannaal from the greatest to the least went under the knife. Those that attempted to flee found the gate guards dead at the hands of a skeletal minion which fought with a skill and toughness out of proportion to that normally displayed by constructs of this sort. Thanks to the enchantments of Cora and Ephantasy. <br>
<br>
As the slaughter continued passers by began to gather to listen to the screams and cries that came from the old shrine. Blood flowed out from under the door and glistened wetly on the window panes, a dark rain was falling on the house Vlos’Shannaal.<br>
<br>
By midmorning the blood harvest was over. All three were drenched, it matted their hair, skin and clothes making them stiff. The chalice hummed with energy, it had been nearly a century since it had been put to its proper use. A purple aura surrounded the chalice and the young cleric.<br>
<br>
“Have you found the documents?” Maelgroth asked his brother.<br>
<br>
“It was difficult to find and disarm the traps, but we have the heart of this house.” Malingrad gestured to an ornate wooden chest which held hundreds of scrolls, inside lay the secrets of many houses. Malingrad was relieved that the Vlos’Shannaal had not invested in a true vault like the Waes’Harventhars it had taken nearly all his skill to simply find the chest, he put it down to the blessing of Innoruuk that he had not died to any of the myriad traps that riddled it.<br>
<br>
“What now?” Bliss sighed, the energy the chalice was giving out was intoxicating. The god was very pleased by this sacrifice.<br>
<br>
“With these documents we could set ourselves up in their place!” Malingrad shouted. He was eager to begin to root through the documents, desperate to confirm rumors heard in the mess hall of the Ebon Mask.<br>
<br>
“We could indeed, but we would have to use some if this information to let all the houses know we possess it. If we did not, they would move against us, hoping to claim this information themselves. We need allies, not enemies. We shall not build our house on paper.” Maelgroth replied, tossing a torch into the chest. The fire greedily devoured the documents.<br>
<br>
“Give this to the chief priests.” Maelgroth handed a note to Blisshadow. “And return the chalice to its proper home.”<br>
