Blisshadow exited the Vlos’Shannaal manse alone. Her brothers remaining behind to discourage looting and to root out any additional members who might have been missed in the initial sweep of the house. As she walked down the black marble steps the small crowd of passersby parted before her. It was the first time in her life anyone had actually shown her respect and she liked it.<br>
<br>
She began her walk to the temple, holding the brimming Blood Chalice before her with both hands. Energy pulsed in the air, radiating from the bloody cup, causing her hair to crackle as she walked. Most of the crowd followed her, being curious to see what would happen next. She could hear the spectators speculating on what had happened in the dark mansion they were leaving behind. She ignored any questions directed towards herself.<br>
<br>
The guard over the moat at the temple had been doubled at the approach of the crowd, when they saw Blisshadow and the chalice they too stepped aside and allowed her to enter unhindered. The crowd they stopped.<br>
The stir her arrival caused at the temple was remarkable. She strode directly to the high altar of the god of hate and placed the chalice in its proper place. As she did so an intense shriek rose from the bloody cup as the souls of the Vlos’Shannal were devoured by the god. <br>
<br>
“Well done.” High priest Valben growled. He was annoyed that he had not been privy to this action, and was angry that he had not been the one to take credit with the god for the sacrifice.<br>
<br>
Bliss was startled out of her ecstatic state by the priest’s voice.<br>
<br>
“I can only assume you are acting at the request of one of the great houses?” He continued. Why they had chosen a nobody to carry out their vendetta against the Vlos’Shannaal instead of someone of importance like himself was a mystery. He had his own score to settle with that house as he was sure most of the powerful did.<br>
<br>
She handed him the packet her brother had given her.<br>
<br>
“So your time with the god has struck you mute, eh, if only that were the case more often.” Valben chuckled as he took the packet.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>That which was once given freely to the god and taken away by the godless has been returned. We would truly appreciate your promotion of this most excellent cleric to the position of priestess in charge of the restored shrine to Innoruuk.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
That was all there was to the note. He looked questioningly back at the priestess. She was busy with her backpack, totally oblivious to his impatience. He had no doubt now that she was the bastard daughter of some noble house looking to find a place for its byblows, their wishes would be accommodated.<br>
<br>
“I am to promote you to priestess and place you in charge of the old Vlos’Shannaal shrine. Tell me, to which house do we owe this great gift?”<br>
<br>
“KNOW THIS PRIEST, I AM WELL PLEASED BY THE WORK DONE THIS NIGHT, WASTE NOT THIS OPPORTUNITY!” The voice was the god’s. The priestess collapsed.<br>
<br>
“Yatva! Come here!” The high priest shouted. Already lesser church functionaries were rushing into the nave, called by the voice of the god of hate. The priest needed his pet bureaucrat to set things in order.<br>
<br>
The portly Teir’Dal appeared at his side moments later. “What can I do for you master?”<br>
<br>
“This one is to be promoted and placed in charge of the old Vlos’Shannaal shrine.” He said indicating the fallen cleric. “It is the will of the god.”<br>
<br>
“Of course, I am sure the Vlos’Shannaal will give her a warm welcome.”<br>
<br>
“I am afraid the Blood Chalice are no longer in charge of that shrine, as a matter of fact, let it be known that the same fate will befall any house that refuses the tithe of hate.” Valben picked up the backpack and looked inside<br>
<br>
“What fate is that master? Have the Vlos’Shannaal fallen out of favor?” <br>
<br>
“So it would appear.” Valben replied, upending the pack. A cascade of freshly skinned faces fluttered to the floor like leaves in Nektulos forest.<br>
<br>
Nystyre was sitting in his carriage looking at the outer gate to the temple of Innorruk. It was good to see a return to the old ways. Hammered into the teak gate with bronze nails were the faces of the entire Vlos’Shannaal house from the greatest to the least. It was a display not seen in several centuries. Attendance at ritual had increased ten fold, mostly as the curious went to look at the faces on the gate. House D’Vir had always paid its tithe and he chuckled to himself that what had been considered a waste of money by many in his own house was now seen as a shrewd political ploy.<br>
<br>
The city was aflame with wild rumor about what had really gone on the Vlos’Shannaal shrine, the greatest attention being paid to the destruction of the house vault and the loss of its secrets. That was something that intrigued him the most. Most houses would have attempted to use the power kept in that vault to further their own ends, and earned the hatred of the rest of their peers. Attempts to reconstruct the documents found in the empty house had met with failure, despite revealing that those charred ashes were indeed t he true documents. He for one was glad that information was lost, there were several indiscretions of his youth that were no doubt chronicled there.<br>
<br>
The gossip amused him. After all he knew the truth about the events the night previous. In fact, the truth was there for anyone with an appreciation of history to see. This was not a vendetta over attempted blackmail as so many believed. This act was based on a much older feud, the one that brought the Vlos’Shannaal to prominence. As he looked at the faces fluttering in the breeze he wondered how many recalled that aside from engraving invitations and chronicling the deeds of the great houses, the Waes’Harventhars had also served the church as inquisitors.<br>
<br>
He was certainly looking forward to his niece’s ascension day… <br>
