“There is another suitor at the gate master.” Vilkev the door warden announced. Suitors had been arriving all day, this being one of the preliminary functions for Athava’s ascension. <br>
<br>
“Really, how wonderful.” Nystrye muttered sarcastically. He hated this part of the ritual, it seemed every house in Neriak trotted out all their available males, be they in diapers or using a cane, just to gawp at his house and eat his food. The gifts were predictable as were the proposals. Just about everyone knew that Athava had been promised from birth to another house, this was simply more tasteful display and pageantry that masked the vicious infighting that was a part of daily life in Neriak. Still it was nice to have the opportunity to look one’s enemies in the eye for a change. He felt very much like one of his hunting dogs curled up in front of the fire surrounded by yapping puppies that insist on attracting his attention.<br>
<br>
“House Jindrun’Belbol!” Vilkev droned in his most impersonal voice, even though it was a house name he had never uttered in his many years as protocol master of house D’Vir.<br>
<br>
Nystyre smiled, a genuine smile for the first time that afternoon. Jindrun’Belbol indeed, the name translated literally to ‘Face Giver” but most likely meant ‘Gift of Honor’. He had been expecting this guest.<br>
<br>
He surveyed the rest of the gathered houses before turning to greet this guest. All faces were turned towards the marble pillared door, most bore the bored expression he was still struggling to maintain. A few, most notably the Chath’elg’Caress and the Ragar’Golhyrr gaped openly. It was obvious each thought the other had this house in their pay. Both had come to this affair hoping to gain the support of some of the other noble houses in their war. It was bleeding both white, but it was quickly becoming apparent that the Fire Hags were going to loose.<br>
<br>
“It was a pleasure to receive your reply to our invitation.” Nystyre replied formally turning to greet his guest. In fact he had taken to carrying the response tattooed into living elf skin with him everywhere. It was delightfully warm and pliable, very soothing to touch.<br>
<br>
“Please accept this gift of respect from our house.” Jindrun’Belbol replied in the old tongue. He was wearing the same courting mask that had been displayed at the Chath’elg’Caress ascension. The robe was similar, black bristle silk from Kunark, cut in a style similar to that popular today, but an original masterwork from centuries ago. It was a robe fitting for a Teir’Dal noble. He extended a small treantwood box.<br>
<br>
Nystyre took the newcomer’s hand in his and exchanged the gesture of peace after receiving the box. It was time to see what this pup was made of. “We are taking great interest in your activites, Waes’Harventhar.” The last being whispered so only the two of them could hear.<br>
<br>
He had been expecting a reaction, and he got one. The eyes behind the mask suddenly locked onto his own, he sensed the pride that the listener took in the fact that his true name was on the lips of the great houses once again, even if it was in a whisper. There was no fear in this one, only cold determination.<br>
<br>
The greeting ended, house Jindrun’Belbol stode purposefully away, towards the rest of the guests awaiting a moment to present themselves to Athava.<br>
<br>
He opened the box. Inside was a single bronze nail, identical to those affixing the faces of the Vlos’Shannal to the temple doors. Nystyre chuckled softly, here was a valuable gift. <br>
<br>
He looked about for his new “neice” and spotted her in the shadows. Vynna K’yari had not yet been officially presented at court and was something of a mystery to the guests as well. She was absolutely stunning in the silversilk dress and platinum tiara, too bad most of the guests did not seem to notice her. He smiled to himself once again, it was probably for the best that she was hiding from the guests, and he was relieved there appeared to be no place to hide any additional items that might find their way into a pocket or purse.<br>
<br>
Vynna noticed his gaze though, and with a sultry wink in his direction she fluttered off in pursuit of Jindrun’Belbol.<br>
<br>
The newcomer was politely ignoring the stares and questions being put to him by the lesser houses who swarmed about him like flies. The higher status houses ignored him publicly pretending to know who he was and what he was doing, but to her trained senses their hunger for information was palpable.<br>
<br>
The afternoon had begun with little fanfare, her arrival in what she thought was appropriate attire had been easy enough. Vilkev had met her at the door, and immediately directed her upstairs where Nystyre was waiting for her. It was the first time she had ever openly entered the house.<br>
<br>
“Not bad, but as a representative of house D’Vir you will have to do better.” <br>
<br>
Kyri was about to take issue at that comment, why she had stolen oneof the finest gowns in Neriak. That was until she saw the dazzling dress Nystyre held out for her.<br>
<br>
In truth, she had never really had much interest in this world, other than as a source of quick cash from foolish nobles. She found their ritual and formalities boring and incomprehensible. Now she was beginning to appreciate the subtleties of the game and with that appreciation came a fascination with its intricacies. <br>
<br>
“I see you like the dress.”<br>
<br>
“It…its beautiful.”<br>
<br>
“Yes, and we will make you so as well. Try not to torment Vilkev too much over the next few hours, I have other matters to attend to, but I will check in with you as soon as I might.” Nystyre replied, handing her the dress and ordering Vilkev to enter.<br>
<br>
“I understand you are our cousin, freshly returned from Mistmoore?” Vilkev announced. His tone more than told her that he did not believe any of her cover story, but that he would play along. He walked over to her, appraising her much like she examined a fine bit of jewelry before she stole it.<br>
<br>
“A bath, a haircut, another bath and a manicure is in order.” He clapped his hands together at the last and a flock of servants appeared and whisked Kyri away. The next hour was full of the most delicious pampering she had ever received. She appreciated the way the staff kept her naked and busy most of the time, giving her no opportunities to properly case the building or to palm a few valuables. Their behavior was totally un-necessary as Kyri had given her word to behave herself.<br>
<br>
When they were done and Kyri had slithered into her dress. There was a knock on her door.<br>
<br>
“This, goes with the dress, neice.” Nystyre handed her a small box.<br>
<br>
Tentatively she opened it, inside was the most exquisite tiara. She had made a point of laughing at tiara wearing princesses wherever possible, and had stolen quite a few in her time, being amazed at the aftermarket interest in such ridiculous headgear.<br>
<br>
“Let me show you how it goes.” He took the platinum dream and gently placed it on her head.<br>
<br>
She wished, for the first time in a while, that she had a mirror in which to see what she looked like, part of her was terrified that the would break out in laughter, a smaller but increasingly vocal was curious to see if she could measure up to those snooty nobles. Still she had taken to avoiding mirrors after a particularly nasty experience in the Plane of Disease.<br>
<br>
“There is a mirror in the next room if you are interested in seeing what you look like Vynna.”<br>
