“You have not yet ascended?” the matron asked, smiling sweetly, yet barely able to hide the hunger behind her eyes. “We should talk, our house has several new bachelors now looking for mates, I am sure a woman of your position would be eager to join a house such as ours.”<br>
<br>
Kyri was amazed at this bald faced plea, the Fire Hags must truly be in desperate straits to make such an open offer. “Patron Nystyre handles my affairs, I am sure he would be eager to hear your proposal.” The smile she returned to this drowning matron was truly chilling, it was one of her favorite smiles, reserved for when she slipped her blade directly into the spine of her enemies. Despite the lack of blood on the floor, it was what she had done. As the matron scuttled off to speak with Maelgroth, she wondered if the Patron of the Chath’elg’Caress yet lived and if she would offer her withered self as a prize to an unknown house to save her family.<br>
<br>
“Jindrun’Belbol is it? I thought you were Jindurn’Plynnar?” the matron of the Chath’elg’Caress whispered a bit too testily, it had been a age since anyone dared to mock her at a public gathering, yet tonight she felt the wolves circling, the attitude of that cousin of the D’Vir’s was just the beginning of the humiliation that was coming, of that she was sure.<br>
<br>
“To some we give, to others we take.” Maelgroth replied.<br>
<br>
“Your attitude shows a certain lack of respect, and the mask you wear reveals your shame in your house.” The matron hissed back. She knew enough of the old days to know such words more often than not resulted in duels.<br>
<br>
“We may wear a mask, but it is out of respect to our host, before the end, you will know all there is to know of shame and lack of respect.” The eyes behind the mask were as cold as velium.<br>
<br>
“I have never…!” the matron began, but her cry of outrage was drowned by the cacophony of laughter that bubbled up around her like quicksand. Realizing the night, and probably the house war, was over for her, she collected what little pride she had left and stalked out of the manse.<br>
<br>
“Well said!” a new voice boomed. It belonged to Ayon’daro of the  Ragar’Golhyrr. This evening only served to underscore the power of his house. Sure it was costing them a pretty penny to destroy the fire hags, and there had been a number of assassinations on his side of the war, but it was obvious to all who was going to win.<br>
<br>
“I feel we owe you something of a debt.” He began cautiously. <br>
<br>
“Really?” Maelgroth replied.<br>
<br>
“Well, without that nudge I fear that witch would still be here plotting against my house.” He stuck his hand out to initiate the gesture of peace.<br>
<br>
“Well, it was nothing, and we are sure we will be able to balance the scales between our houses soon.”<br>
<br>
“Indeed, that would be wonderful.” Ayon’daro chortled, the mask was giving him fits, he was almost sure he had met this person before, but without a face to put with a house name he was lost.<br>
<br>
“It will be a most notable day.” The young necromancer replied. He had noticed the stunning Teir’Dal stalking him earlier in the evening. She was a study in contradictions. She walked like a hunter yet had difficulty from time to time fending off the advances of some of the other houses. He felt he had seen her before, it was just the setting that was throwing him off, he was sure of that. As he looked of the Truth Finder’s shoulder at her he realized with a start, she was letting him see her. His eyes flicked over to Nystyre. <br>
<br>
The patron of D’Vir was looking at him with an amused expression. Could it be he was being set up for an alliance with this cousin? The thought terrified him. For all his life the family had concentrated on getting their revenge, and not enough time thinking about what would happen afterwards, he would have to speak with his mother about this. Suddenly he realized he had spent too long at this party.<br>
<br>
He turned his gaze back on the Ragar’Golhyrr, he was blathering on about how powerful his house was and how they were destroying the Chath’elg’Caress.<br>
<br>
“Has your house had any great moments like these? Ayon’daro muttered, he was eager to get as much information from this unknown house as possible.<br>
<br>
“No one has been foolish enough to move against our house for some time.” Maelgroth growled. “What do you think happened to the Vlos’Shannaal?” It was a topic of endless discussion.<br>
<br>
“We think they crossed the wrong house.” He laughed, and swallowed some more wine.<br>
<br>
“Indeed, they did.” Maelgroth laughed with him. “Pardon me, we must pay my respects to Athava.”<br>
<br>
Athava was no beauty, she was a knight of the lodge of the Dead, and Mael had seen her about the temple when he was a student. He was surprised to sense he had eclipsed her in power.<br>
<br>
He initiated the gesture of peace. “You would be more comfortable killing Feir’Dal I believe.”<br>
<br>
“Indeed, I would, I have little patience for such affairs.” She growled, looking scornfully over at her arranged mate, a wispy looking wizard, preening like a drunken aviak in front of a mirror.<br>
<br>
“Well, I am sure you will have him whipped into shape in no time.” Mael grinned. He had heard all about Athava’s appetites when he was at school.<br>
<br>
“I suppose you are right, I should be looking forward to this evening!” the guest of honor perked up. It would be a pleasure breaking this one to her will permanently. <br>
<br>
Maelgroth left the young and now eager ascendant to be with a smile on her face. It would be a brutal and efficient courtship, of that he was sure. With a bow of respect he headed towards the gate.<br>
<br>
“Do you require a carriage, sir?” Vilkev droned. There were several teak carriages in the courtyard waiting to return guests to their own manse. Each bore the mark of House D’Vir an assault on a guest returning from this affair would have to reckon with their anger.<br>
<br>
Tentatively, Maelgroth looked around, there nearby stood Vynna K’yari, Nystyre’s cousin. No one else seemed to notice her. That settled it for him. It must be a trap. Entering into a formal alliance with house D’Vir, attending an ascension of his own, suddenly scared him more than taking on four powerful houses in third gate. For a moment he considered taking a carriage, he knew she would be there, somehow. Where could he take her, certainly not home to the shack in the foreign quarter.<br>
<br>
He looked back at her, she was staring at him intently, she was about to say something, he was sure of it. <br>
<br>
He gated back to his quarters.<br>
